In Series #3, we built a Runtime Component Registry capable of dynamically loading client-specific features on demand without inflating the core bundle size. However, once your application can dynamically fetch and render isolated components, it faces its next major architectural bottleneck: navigation.
In a traditional React application, routing is defined statically. We declare paths, components, and hierarchies upfront using tools like React Router or TanStack Router:
TypeScript
// ❌ The Monolithic Approach: Hardcoded, Static Routes
export const AppRoutes = () => (
<BrowserRouter>
<Routes>
<Route path="/dashboard" element={<Dashboard />} />
<Route path="/loans" element={<LoansPage />} /> {/* What if Bank B doesn't have loans? */}
<Route path="/investments" element={<InvestmentsPage />} /> {/* What if Bank A doesn't have investments? */}
</Routes>
</BrowserRouter>
);When managing thousands of enterprise tenants, this approach fails completely. Bank A might want its entry point at /banking/summary, Bank B might require a flat structure like /invest-portal, and Bank C might require entirely different nested layouts depending on regional compliance rules. Hardcoding these paths breaks tenant isolation and creates versioning chaos.
To scale seamlessly, the routing system must treat navigation as data. This article explores how to construct a dynamic, schema-driven routing tree mapped entirely at runtime based on the authenticated tenant’s context.
The Dynamic Routing Blueprint
Instead of relying on a static map, the core platform acts as an unmapped canvas. At bootstrap, the platform reads the tenant’s metadata manifest, builds a dynamic route matrix, translates layout definitions into live components using the runtime registry, and injects the configuration into the active browser navigation context.
